Process called "split_string" that takes string as String and delimiter as String returns List[String]:
    Note: Split string by delimiter into list of substrings
    If length of delimiter is equal to 0:
        Return list containing string
    
    Let result be list containing
    Let current_part be ""
    Let i be 0
    Let string_length be length of string
    Let delimiter_length be length of delimiter
    
    While i is less than string_length:
        Let matches_delimiter be true
        
        For j from 0 to delimiter_length minus 1:
            If i plus j is greater than or equal to string_length:
                Set matches_delimiter to false
                Break
            If character_at with string as string and index as (i plus j) is not equal to character_at with string as delimiter and index as j:
                Set matches_delimiter to false
                Break
        
        If matches_delimiter:
            Add current_part to result
            Set current_part to ""
            Set i to i plus delimiter_length
        Otherwise:
            Set current_part to current_part plus character_at with string as string and index as i
            Set i to i plus 1
    
    Add current_part to result
    Return result

Process called "slice_list" that takes lst as List[Any] and start as Integer and end as Integer returns List[Any]:
    Note: Extract slice of list from start to end (exclusive)
    Let list_length be length of lst
    
    Note: Handle negative indices
    If start is less than 0:
        Set start to list_length plus start
    If end is less than 0:
        Set end to list_length plus end
    
    Note: Clamp to valid range
    If start is less than 0:
        Set start to 0
    If start is greater than list_length:
        Set start to list_length
    If end is less than 0:
        Set end to 0
    If end is greater than list_length:
        Set end to list_length
    
    Note: Handle invalid range
    If start is greater than or equal to end:
        Return list containing
    
    Let result be list containing
    For i from start to end minus 1:
        Add (lst at index i) to result
    
    Return result

Process called "extract_function_source" that takes source_code as String and function_name as String returns String:
    Note: Extract source code of a specific function from full source
    Try:
        Let lines be split_string with string as source_code and delimiter as "\n"
        Let function_start be negative 1
        Let function_end be negative 1
        Let indentation_level be 0
        
        Note: Find function definition
        For i from 0 to length of lines minus 1:
            Let line be lines at index i
            Let trimmed_line be trim_whitespace with string as line
            
            If contains_substring with string as trimmed_line and substring as "Process called" and contains_substring with string as trimmed_line and substring as function_name:
                Set function_start to i
                Set indentation_level to count_leading_spaces with string as line
                Break
        
        If function_start is equal to negative 1:
            Return "Function not found"
        
        Note: Find function end (next function or end of file)
        Set function_end to length of lines
        For i from function_start plus 1 to length of lines minus 1:
            Let line be lines at index i
            Let current_indentation be count_leading_spaces with string as line
            Let trimmed_line be trim_whitespace with string as line
            
            If length of trimmed_line is greater than 0 and current_indentation is less than or equal to indentation_level and contains_substring with string as trimmed_line and substring as "Process called":
                Set function_end to i
                Break
        
        Note: Extract function source
        Let result be ""
        For i from function_start to function_end minus 1:
            Set result to result plus (lines at index i) plus "\n"
        
        Return result
    Catch error:
        Return source_code

Process called "compare_signatures" that takes sig1 as FunctionSignature and sig2 as FunctionSignature returns Boolean:
    Note: Compare two function signatures for equality
    Try:
        Note: Compare parameter count
        If length of sig1.parameter_names is not equal to length of sig2.parameter_names:
            Return false
        
        Note: Compare parameter names
        For i from 0 to length of sig1.parameter_names minus 1:
            If sig1.parameter_names at index i is not equal to sig2.parameter_names at index i:
                Return false
        
        Note: Compare parameter types if available
        If length of sig1.parameter_types is equal to length of sig2.parameter_types:
            For i from 0 to length of sig1.parameter_types minus 1:
                If sig1.parameter_types at index i is not equal to sig2.parameter_types at index i:
                    Return false
        
        Note: Compare return type
        If sig1.return_type is not equal to sig2.return_type:
            Return false
        
        Note: Compare varargs and kwargs
        If sig1.has_varargs is not equal to sig2.has_varargs:
            Return false
        If sig1.has_kwargs is not equal to sig2.has_kwargs:
            Return false
        
        Return true
    Catch error:
        Return false

